"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:5.21.4\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">5.21.4</span> Birthstool</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Reference:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">אָבְנַיִם</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(’ovnayim)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod1:16\">EXO 1:16</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description and usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>The birthstool was a special seat, perhaps made of two stones side by side with a space between them, on which a woman sat to give birth.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>The Hebrew word <em>’ovnayim</em> literally means “pair of stones” or “double stone.” Lexicographers and commentators differ concerning its meaning in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod1:16\">EXO 1:16</a>. In <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer18:3\">JER 18:3</a> the same word refers to the potter’s wheel (see <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">1.5.1.1 Potter’s wheel&lt;REALIA:1.5.1.1&gt;</a>). The dictionaries offer two probable meanings: (1) it may be a euphemism to refer to the genitals, so the second clause in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod1:16\">EXO 1:16</a> may be rendered “you will look to see if the baby is a boy”); or (2) it may designate a birthstool because of a certain resemblance to the potter’s bench, so the same clause may be rendered “you will watch as they give birth.” The context allows either interpretation.</p>\n<p>It is not necessary to give a literal translation; for the first half of this verse, compare <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr> “When you help the Hebrew women give birth.” Where such a stool or chair is known, of course, it may be used here. <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New International Version (1984)\">NIV</abbr> has “When you help the Hebrew women in childbirth and observe them on the delivery stool.” here. <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New International Version (1984)\">NIV</abbr> has “When you help the Hebrew women in childbirth and observe them on the delivery stool.”</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
